    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ab20f00b_68fdf85e",
        "filename": "src/gpu/ops/GrQuadPerEdgeAA.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 280,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-05T20:51:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This one function accounts for a large fraction of the code change to GrQuadPerEdgeAA. It could be replaced with something similar to get_area_coverage in SampleDegenerateQuad (see above, but would not need to include the non-AA handling).\n\nHowever, when using any CTM other than translating, or non-axis-aligned geometry, this function is about 30X faster than the much smaller code relying on SkPath and an intersection op.\n\nMaybe that means it\u0027s worth exposing somewhere in the GPU folder, but I don\u0027t know if there are other places that would need the intersection of a rectangle and a quad. Its structure is definitely tied strictly to those geometric assumptions.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 280,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 280,
        "endChar": 31
      },
      "revId": "4551a9fe682011fd84bbab80f4a0aaadad3f8ce3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "59a757be_540e6e92",
        "filename": "src/gpu/ops/GrQuadPerEdgeAA.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 280,
      "author": {
        "id": 5633
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-08T17:10:04Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e This one function accounts for a large fraction of the code change to GrQuadPerEdgeAA. It could be replaced with something similar to get_area_coverage in SampleDegenerateQuad (see above, but would not need to include the non-AA handling).\n\u003e \n\u003e However, when using any CTM other than translating, or non-axis-aligned geometry, this function is about 30X faster than the much smaller code relying on SkPath and an intersection op.\n\u003e \n\u003e Maybe that means it\u0027s worth exposing somewhere in the GPU folder, but I don\u0027t know if there are other places that would need the intersection of a rectangle and a quad. Its structure is definitely tied strictly to those geometric assumptions.\n\nI had a couple questions here.\n\nMy understanding from the code is, this is called when the quad is smaller than a pixel, correct? So my questions are:\n\n1) How important is it to get exact coverage, as opposed to a simple approximation?\n2) How are pixel-size quads handled, that straddle 4 corners equally?",
      "parentUuid": "ab20f00b_68fdf85e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 280,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 280,
        "endChar": 31
      },
      "revId": "4551a9fe682011fd84bbab80f4a0aaadad3f8ce3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "36145faa_9b9e28e2",
        "filename": "src/gpu/ops/GrQuadPerEdgeAA.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 280,
      "author": {
        "id": 5633
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-08T17:25:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My line of thinking was:\n\nA single convex polygon can be drawn fairly simply with AA outset geometry and 0..1 coverage ramps. Corners aren\u0027t very important (if just drawing a single convex shape) so those can also be simple coverage ramps.\n\nAs we\u0027ve discussed before, any subdivision of the quad is done with hard edges, so we can just do exact chops there on the original (simple) geometry.\n\nSo could we, instead, generate some simple geometry that draws the original quad (any technique we want for the corners and ramps.. doesn\u0027t really matter), then just clip that geometry? Could we then not have to worry about all this complexity here, and instead only need to implement one function that chops coverage ramp geometry in half?",
      "parentUuid": "59a757be_540e6e92",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 280,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 280,
        "endChar": 31
      },
      "revId": "4551a9fe682011fd84bbab80f4a0aaadad3f8ce3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "99d833df_c8e4ca3d",
        "filename": "src/gpu/ops/GrQuadPerEdgeAA.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 280,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-08T18:54:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "First comment responses first:\n1. I explored simple approximations first, using the shortest edges or the shortest diagonals, and it just didn\u0027t look as good to me. Tended to create visual pops in coverage when transitioning from a regular to degenerate interior.\n2. So, when this is evaluated, it uses a hypothetical pixel located exactly at the vertex. For a pixel-size quad, the interior maps to a central point, so it\u0027s independent of how the quad lines up with the actual pixel grid. In this case, it\u0027d calculate coverage close to 1, and then with its outset coverage ramps, the 4 touched pixels would each see a distributed lower coverage value.  Testing the scenario in the SampleDegenerateQuad slide looks reasonable.\n\nSecond comment responses:\nYes absolutely, this would be a lot easier if we calculated the AA geometry for the intended complete layer, and then chopped it up. Unfortunately that\u0027s not what they give us and all of the code that handles the chops are controlled by non-virtual methods higher up in the compositor system. When we can take over at that level, we will avoid a lot of these hassles and can probably get away with simpler subpixel approximations again (or go back to the wider thin-aa method)",
      "parentUuid": "36145faa_9b9e28e2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 280,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 280,
        "endChar": 31
      },
      "revId": "4551a9fe682011fd84bbab80f4a0aaadad3f8ce3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f2eb4ac0_5dadcba5",
        "filename": "src/gpu/ops/GrQuadPerEdgeAA.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 453,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-05T20:51:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "An unfortunate consequence of  relying on edge intersections to calculate the new coordinates is that two adjacent quads now calculate their shared corner based one shared edge, and one \"parallel\" edge from a corner the other quad cannot know about.\n\noutset_projected_vertices helps counteract this by solving for edge coefficients to get to the intersection, but still respect the AA edge mask. Unfortunately, it\u0027s possible for two adjacent quads to calculate their projected corners in slightly different locations and still cause pixel acne along their edge. At this point it is very rare, though.",
      "revId": "4551a9fe682011fd84bbab80f4a0aaadad3f8ce3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bef853df_74cf518e",
        "filename": "src/gpu/ops/GrQuadPerEdgeAA.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 542,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-05T20:51:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "While the code is heavily modified from before (due to the struct refactoring), the logic here is mostly the same. The only other major deviation is the manner in which degenerate quads are handled. \n\nTo work correctly with the AA tiling needs in SkiaRenderer, the thin line AA approach of outsetting to a fixed 2px doesn\u0027t really work. The implementation also relied strongly on a rectangular shape assumption. So, anything too small or with bad angles goes through the degenerate code path.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 542,
        "startChar": 12,
        "endLine": 542,
        "endChar": 40
      },
      "revId": "4551a9fe682011fd84bbab80f4a0aaadad3f8ce3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ece8bf30_0a5dfe99",
        "filename": "src/gpu/ops/GrQuadPerEdgeAA.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 553,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-05T20:51:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It may make sense for get_optimized_outset to return if the optimized outset procedure can be used for the outer and inner quads separately. In most cases, the optimal path can always be used. In most cases where the degenerate code path will be needed, it\u0027s to handle just the inset.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 553,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 553,
        "endChar": 28
      },
      "revId": "4551a9fe682011fd84bbab80f4a0aaadad3f8ce3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c09333ad_57effcad",
        "filename": "src/gpu/ops/GrQuadPerEdgeAA.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 572,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-05T20:51:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is a pretty substantial rewrite from what was there before for perspective quads. Given the complexities of handling degenerate quads in 2D, I found it better to route all projected perspective quads through that shared code and then resolve the matching initial shape. The alternative would have been to implement an equivalent 3D degenerate function.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 572,
        "startChar": 12,
        "endLine": 572,
        "endChar": 46
      },
      "revId": "4551a9fe682011fd84bbab80f4a0aaadad3f8ce3",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "560ea74c_a0be41fc",
        "filename": "src/gpu/ops/GrQuadPerEdgeAA.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 631,
